[{"id":30124,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","question":"","options":["Both (A) and (R) are true but (R)&nbsp;is NOT the correct explanation of (A).","(A) is false but (R) is true.","Both (A) and (R) are true and (R) is the correct explanation of (A ).","(A) is true but (R) is false."],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8b6db842-e3f5-4cbe-976f-a7af81a1d23e-image.png\" style=\"width: 515px; height: 103px;\" /></p><p>Markovnikov&#39;s rule of addition : In an electrophilic addition reaction to alkenes and alkynes the electrophile attacks in such a way that a more stable carbocation intermediate is formed on which nucleophile attacks in the next step.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30127,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","question":"","options":["Statement I&nbsp;is true but Statement II&nbsp;is false.","Both Statement I and Statement II are true.","Both Statement I and Statement II are false.","Statement I&nbsp;is false but Statement II&nbsp;is true."],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Sphalerite&nbsp;is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ZnS</mi></math></p><p>Copper glance is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cu</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></math></p><p>It is possible to separate two sulphide ores by adjusting proportion of oil to water or by using &#39;depressants&#39;. For example, in case of an ore containing <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ZnS</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>PbS</mi></math>, the depressant used is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaCN</mi></math>. It selectively prevents <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ZnS</mi></math> from coming to the froth but allows <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>PbS</mi></math> to come with the froth.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30134,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","question":"","options":["(A) is calcination and (B) is roasting","Both (A) and (B) are producing same product so both are roasting","Both (A) and (B) are producing same product so both are calcination","(A) is roasting and (B) is calcination"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>(A)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>ZnCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi></mfenced><mover><mo>&#10230;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi></mover><mi>ZnO</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>Heating in absence of oxygen in calcination.</p><p>(B)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>Zns</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>ZnO</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>heating in presence of oxygen in roasting Hence (A)&nbsp;is calcination while (B) in roasting.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30174,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","question":"","options":["Azurite","Malachite","Dolomite","Copper pyrites"],"answer":3,"solution":"Azurite <math><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>C</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>C</mi><msub><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>.</mo><mi>C</mi><mi>u</mi><msub><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi>O</mi><mi>H</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math><br /><br />Dolomite - <math><mi>C</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>C</mi><msub><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>.</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>g</mi><mi>C</mi><msub><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math> ,<br /><br />Malachite <math><mo>-</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>C</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>C</mi><msub><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>.</mo><mi>C</mi><mi>u</mi><msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>O</mi><mi>H</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math><br /><br />Copper pyrites <math><mo>-</mo></math> <math><mi>C</mi><mi>u</mi><mi>F</mi><mi>e</mi><msub><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>,</mo></math><br /><br />So both copper and Iron are present in copper pyrite.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30144,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">q</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></mfenced></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Kernite <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></p><p>The chemical formula for Kernite is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><mn>4</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>. It contains boron.</p><p>Cassiterite <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>SnO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math></p><p>Cassiterite is an ore of&nbsp;Sn.It &nbsp;is&nbsp;also called&nbsp;tinstone and has molecular formula of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SnO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>â€‹.</p><p>Calamine <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>ZnCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p>Calamine is an ore of&nbsp;zinc.&nbsp;It is zinc carbonate&nbsp;ZnCO<sub>3</sub>â€‹.</p><p>Cryolite <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>Na</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>AlF</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math>, which consists of Aluminium, Sodium &amp; Fluorine.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30185,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mi>dilute</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mo>H</mo><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mover><msub><mi>FeSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mo>O</mo><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mover><msub><mi>Fe</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>heat</mi></mover><mi>Fe</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>heat</mo></mrow></mover><mi>FeO</mi><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mi>dilute</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mo>H</mo><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mover><msub><mi>FeSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>heat</mi></mover><mi>Fe</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>heat</mo></mrow></mover><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mi>heat</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>air</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>Zn</mi></mover><mi>Fe</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>heat</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi>Fe</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mi>CO</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>600</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8451;</mi></mrow></mover><mi>FeO</mi><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mi>CO</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>700</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#8451;</mi></mrow></mover><mi>Fe</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"This is the blast furnace reaction.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mtext>Fe</mtext><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mi>dilute</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mo>H</mo><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mover><msub><mi>FeSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mover><msub><mi>Fe</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>heat</mi></mover><mi>Fe</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mtext>Fe</mtext><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>heat</mi></mrow></mover><mi>FeO</mi><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mi>dilute</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mo>H</mo><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mover><msub><mi>FeSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>heat</mi></mover><mi>Fe</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> cannot be the answer&nbsp;since, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math> on heating gives <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>FeO</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>.<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mi>Fe</mi><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>heat</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mi>heat</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>air</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mi>Zn</mi></mover><mi>Fe</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> is wrong because <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>, on heating in air, stays as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Fe</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math> and does not form <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>FeCl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (06 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30138,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)-(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>),&#160;(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)-(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>),(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)-(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>),(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)-(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)-(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)&#160;</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)-(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>), (</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)-(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>), (</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)-(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>), (</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)-(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>ii</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iv</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>-</mo><mo>(</mo><mi>iii</mi><mo>)</mo></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<table border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width: 500px;\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>&nbsp;</td>\t\t\t<td>Ore</td>\t\t\t<td>Formula</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>a</td>\t\t\t<td>Haematite</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Fe</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>b</td>\t\t\t<td>Bauxite</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><msub><mi>xH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>c</td>\t\t\t<td>Magnetite</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Fe</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>d</td>\t\t\t<td>Malachite</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CuCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><mi>Cu</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msub></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30098,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Al</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ag</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Fe</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Cyanide process, also called Macarthur-forrest Process, method of extracting silver and gold from their ores by dissolving them in a dilute solution of sodium cyanide or potassium cyanide. The following redox reaction takes place during the extraction process.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi>Ag</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>8</mn><msup><mi>CN</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>[</mo><mi>Ag</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>CN</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>]</mo><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>OH</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>Ag</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>CN</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>+</mo><mi>Zn</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>Ag</mi><mo>&#8595;</mo><mo>+</mo><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>Zn</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>CN</mi></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30118,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>Au</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>CN</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>Zn</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>CN</mi></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>Au</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>CN</mi></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>Zn</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>CN</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>Au</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>CN</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>Zn</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>Au</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>CN</mi></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>Zn</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>CN</mi></mfenced><mn>6</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Extraction of gold&nbsp;is carried out by leaching process.</p><p>Sodium cyanide&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>NaCN</mi><mo>)</mo></math>&nbsp;has been used as leaching reagent for gold.</p><p>Metal is&nbsp;converted into the soluble cyanide complex on reaction with sodium cyanide.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi>Au</mi><mo>&#160;+&#160;8</mo><msup><mi>CN</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">-</mi></msup><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">2</mi></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">2</mi></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><munder><mrow><mo>[</mo><mi>Au</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>CN</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">2</mi></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">]</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">-</mi></msup></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></munder><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>OH</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">-</mi></msup></math></p><p>Silver is later recovered by&nbsp;displacement with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zn</mi></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>Au</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>CN</mi></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">-</mi></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Zn</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mtext>Displacement</mtext></mover><munder><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>Zn</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>CN</mi></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></munder><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>+</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>Au</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>and</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math>&nbsp;are &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>[</mo><mi>Au</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>CN</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">2</mi></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">]</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">-</mi></msup></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;[</mo><mi>Zn</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>CN</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">4</mi></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">]</mi><mi>2-</mi></msup></math>,&nbsp;respectively.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30158,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","question":"","options":["Pig iron is obtained from cast iron.&nbsp;","The Hall-Heroult process is used for the production of aluminium and iron.","leaching of bauxite using concentrated <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> solution gives sodium aluminate and sodium silicate.","the blistered appearance of copper during the metallurgical process is due to the evolution of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>.</mo></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"(1) During leaching when bauxite is treated with concentrated <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>,</mo></math> then sodium aluminate and sodium silicate is formed in the soluble form, whereas <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">F</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub></math> is precipitated<br />(2) The blistered appearance of copper during the metallurgical process is due to evolution of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>.</mo></math><br />(3) Cast iron is obtained from pig iron.<br />(4) Hall-Heroult process is used for production of only aluminium.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30156,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","question":"","options":["liquation.","vapour phase refining.","zone refining.","distillation."],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Liquation method is used when the melting point of metal is less compare to the melting point of the associated impurity.</p><p>In liquation process, the impure metal is heated on slopy hearth of furnace, due to less melting point, metal melts first and flow down leaving impurities behind.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30160,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","question":"","options":["Aniline is a froth stabilizer.","Zone refining process is used for the refining of titanium.","Zincite is a carbonate ore.","Sodium cyanide cannot be used in the metallurgy of silver."],"answer":0,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math> Aniline is the forth stabilizer.<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></math> Zone refining process is not used for refining of <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math> Zincite is <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mrow></mfenced></math> Sodium cyanide is used in the metallurgy of silver","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30117,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true.","Both Statement I and Statement II are false.","Statement I is true but Statement II is false.","Statement I is false but Statement II is true."],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Impure <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi></math> obtained from ores is converted to pure <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi></math> in an electrolyte cell that the impure copper as the anode an pure copper as the cathode. The electrolyte is an aqueous solution of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CuSO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>. At the impure <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi></math> anode, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi></math> is oxidized along with the more easily oxidized metallic impurities such as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Zn</mi></math> and Fe. The less easily oxidized impurities such as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ag</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Au</mi></math>, and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Pt</mi></math> fall to the bottom of the cell as anode mud, which is reprocessed to recover the precious metals. At the pure <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi></math> cathode, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cu</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup></math> ions get reduced to pure copper metal</p><p>Anode (oxidation) :&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced><mo>&#10230;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>Cu</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Zn</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>Fe</mi></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>Cathode (reduction) :&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cu</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>-</mo></msup><mo>&#10230;</mo><mi>Cu</mi><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>Thus, the net cell reaction simply involves transfer of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi></math> metal from the impure anode to the pure cathode, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cu</mi></math> obtained by this process is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>99</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>95</mn><mo>%</mo></math> pure.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30102,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>Cu</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>Cu</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Fe</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>CO</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>FeO</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>NaOH</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>Na</mi><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mi>Al</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>Mg</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>MgO</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>Al</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Leaching: It involves the treatment of the&nbsp;ore with a suitable reagent as to make it soluble&nbsp;while impurity remains insoluble and after this, the ore is recovered from the solution by suitable methods.</p><p>The principal ore of aluminium and&nbsp;bauxite&nbsp;usually contain&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SiO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>, iron oxides and titanium oxides as impurities.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>NaOH</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>Na</mi><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>Al</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mn>2</mn><mi>Na</mi><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mi>Al</mi><msub><mfenced><mi>OH</mi></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>CO</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msub><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced><mo>&#8594;</mo><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo mathvariant=\"bold\">&#183;</mo><msub><mi>xH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>NaHCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>The sodium silicate remains in the solution and hydrated alumina is filtered, dried and heated to give pure&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo mathvariant=\"bold\">&#183;</mo><msub><mi>xH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced><mover><mo>&#8594;</mo><mrow><mn>1470</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></mrow></mover><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></mfenced><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>xH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mfenced></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30147,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"General Principles and Processes of Isolation of Metals","question":"","options":["(a)-(ii), (b)-(iv), (c)-(i), (d)-(iii)","(a)-(iv), (b)-(iii), (c)-(ii), (d)-(i)","(a)-(i), (b)-(ii), (c)-(iii), (d)-(iv)","(a)-(iii), (b)-(i), (c)-(iv), (d)-(ii)"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Siderite<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>FeCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p>Siderite is a mineral composed of iron (II) carbonate (FeCO<sub>3</sub>). It is a widespread mineral that is an ore of iron.&nbsp;</p><p>Calamine<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>ZnCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p>Zinc ore is most commonly found as zinc carbonate&nbsp;(ZnCO<sub>3</sub>â€‹), known as calamine or smithsonite.&nbsp;</p><p>Kaolinite<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>Al</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><msub><mi>Si</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math></p><p>Malachite<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>Cu</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>OH</mi><msub><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#183;</mo><msub><mi>CuCO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 2)","image":null}]